00:00:00.510 --> 00:00:01.501
Voiceover: What I want
to do in this video is

00:00:01.501 --> 00:00:05.242
start to visualize the balance
sheet for a simple bank

00:00:05.242 --> 00:00:07.271
so we can start to understand
the actual mechanics

00:00:07.271 --> 00:00:11.346
for how a bank accounts for
its assets and liabilities

00:00:11.346 --> 00:00:14.516
in the context of a
fractional reserve system.

00:00:14.716 --> 00:00:16.543
First, let's just give a general idea

00:00:16.543 --> 00:00:17.795
of what a balance sheet is,

00:00:17.795 --> 00:00:20.137
and I go into a lot more
depth in other playlists,

00:00:20.137 --> 00:00:22.145
but when we talk about a balance sheet,

00:00:22.145 --> 00:00:23.437
we're really just talking about

00:00:23.437 --> 00:00:25.217
how many assets does something have,

00:00:25.217 --> 00:00:26.905
and how many liabilities offset it,

00:00:26.905 --> 00:00:30.052
and how much is left over
for the owners of the firm

00:00:30.052 --> 00:00:31.833
or whatever we're talking about.

00:00:31.833 --> 00:00:33.206
For example,

00:00:33.206 --> 00:00:35.692
So, for example, if I have, let's say,

00:00:35.692 --> 00:00:38.520
let's just say, generalize
it to any type of company.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:39.689
Let's say that they have,

00:00:39.689 --> 00:00:42.215
so over here, I'll draw their assets,

00:00:42.215 --> 00:00:45.388
so their assets, I'll
do it in this green box.

00:00:45.388 --> 00:00:46.791
The height of it is kind of the magnitude

00:00:46.791 --> 00:00:47.947
of their assets.

00:00:47.947 --> 00:00:49.230
Let's say there's some company

00:00:49.230 --> 00:00:52.494
that has $100 million in assets,

00:00:52.494 --> 00:00:53.984
and assets, you probably understand.

00:00:53.984 --> 00:00:55.963
It's something that gives
you some type of benefit.

00:00:55.963 --> 00:00:57.172
The more formal definition

00:00:57.172 --> 00:00:59.024
is something that gives
you some future value,

00:00:59.024 --> 00:01:00.695
and it's generally considered to have

00:01:00.695 --> 00:01:02.216
some positive economic value,

00:01:02.216 --> 00:01:04.197
so it could be cash because
cash can be converted

00:01:04.197 --> 00:01:05.691
into other things.

00:01:05.691 --> 00:01:06.553
You can go buy a cow,

00:01:06.553 --> 00:01:08.122
and that cow can provide milk for you

00:01:08.122 --> 00:01:09.727
and give you future benefit.

00:01:09.727 --> 00:01:11.118
A cow itself would be an asset.

00:01:11.118 --> 00:01:12.218
A building would be an asset,

00:01:12.218 --> 00:01:13.871
because it gives you the future value

00:01:13.871 --> 00:01:15.786
of giving you shelter,

00:01:15.786 --> 00:01:16.880
so assets could be anything,

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:18.666
but here for the sake of this company,

00:01:18.666 --> 00:01:21.507
we could even visualize
it as cash, if you like.

00:01:21.507 --> 00:01:23.794
It has $100 million of assets,

00:01:23.794 --> 00:01:25.741
and let's say it has some liabilities,

00:01:25.741 --> 00:01:27.566
so let's say this company right over here

00:01:27.566 --> 00:01:29.854
has 60 million in liabilities.

00:01:29.854 --> 00:01:31.939
I'm trying to do it roughly
equal to the height.

00:01:31.939 --> 00:01:33.102
It's not exact,

00:01:33.102 --> 00:01:37.553
but let's say that they have
60 million in liabilities.

00:01:37.553 --> 00:01:39.917
Liabilities are just obligations,

00:01:39.917 --> 00:01:43.919
so it owes people $60
million worth of stuff,

00:01:43.919 --> 00:01:45.185
and so when you look at it this way,

00:01:45.185 --> 00:01:46.720
this entity here,

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:47.966
it could be a company, a firm,

00:01:47.966 --> 00:01:49.651
you could even call this a person,

00:01:49.651 --> 00:01:50.805
if this was a person.

00:01:50.805 --> 00:01:52.804
They have $100 million of assets,

00:01:52.804 --> 00:01:55.265
but they owe 60 million of that 100,

00:01:55.265 --> 00:01:56.538
or you could say they owe 60,

00:01:56.538 --> 00:01:58.377
and you could view it of that 100 million,

00:01:58.377 --> 00:02:00.051
so they would have 40 million left over

00:02:00.051 --> 00:02:00.947
for themselves.

00:02:00.947 --> 00:02:03.780
If you were to say, "What
is the value of this?"

00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:05.387
How much do the owners of this entity,

00:02:05.387 --> 00:02:07.985
actually, how much are they
worth from this entity?

00:02:07.985 --> 00:02:10.283
It would be the 100 minus the 60.

00:02:10.283 --> 00:02:12.406
they have 100, they owe 60,

00:02:12.406 --> 00:02:14.692
so the owner's equity, right over here,

00:02:14.692 --> 00:02:17.222
would be $40 million.

00:02:17.222 --> 00:02:18.784
That's really kind of the value

00:02:18.784 --> 00:02:20.726
of what the owners have,

00:02:20.726 --> 00:02:25.280
and it's called owner's equity.

00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:26.848
That's just a basic primary

00:02:26.848 --> 00:02:28.456
primer in assets and liabilities,

00:02:28.456 --> 00:02:29.346
and now I want to use,

00:02:29.346 --> 00:02:30.843
I want to build on that to think about

00:02:30.843 --> 00:02:31.787
what's actually happening

00:02:31.787 --> 00:02:33.957
in a fractional reserve
system with the bank,

00:02:33.957 --> 00:02:35.102
and what we're going to see is,

00:02:35.102 --> 00:02:36.526
the way it's actually done mechanically

00:02:36.526 --> 00:02:37.924
in a modern fractional reserve system

00:02:37.924 --> 00:02:39.072
is slightly different than

00:02:39.072 --> 00:02:40.493
the way you would conceptualize it,

00:02:40.493 --> 00:02:41.009
the way you,

00:02:41.009 --> 00:02:43.614
actually, I've been
conceptualizing it for you guys,

00:02:43.614 --> 00:02:44.570
because that's just an easier way

00:02:44.570 --> 00:02:46.074
to think about things.

00:02:46.074 --> 00:02:48.235
Let's just say we were
going to go start a bank.

00:02:48.235 --> 00:02:52.126
Let's say I want to start a bank,

00:02:52.126 --> 00:02:55.146
and what I do is I go and I take,

00:02:55.146 --> 00:02:57.001
I go buy a, I don't know.

